00:00:09.701 --> 00:00:10.901
Green: Fantastic.

00:00:10.901 --> 00:00:12.567
So we're gonna talk
a little bit about

00:00:12.567 --> 00:00:14.767
what accessibility means
in products

00:00:14.767 --> 00:00:17.367
and how we can use features
that are built in

00:00:17.367 --> 00:00:19.601
to the platforms
that Google offers.

00:00:19.601 --> 00:00:21.133
Erin, can you go
to the next slide?

00:00:21.133 --> 00:00:22.934
Okay. So just a couple
of questions.

00:00:22.934 --> 00:00:24.367
How many of you
have some experience

00:00:24.367 --> 00:00:27.634
with accessibility technology
already?

00:00:27.634 --> 00:00:29.567
Okay. A little more than half.
That's fantastic.

00:00:29.567 --> 00:00:31.868
How many of you are actually
responsible for building

00:00:31.868 --> 00:00:34.601
accessibility
into your products?

00:00:34.601 --> 00:00:36.267
A couple of us.
Okay, keep your hands up.

00:00:36.267 --> 00:00:38.734
How many of you know the
current gaps in your products

00:00:38.734 --> 00:00:41.167
and know how to fix them?

00:00:41.167 --> 00:00:42.634
Okay. Fair number. Okay.

00:00:42.634 --> 00:00:45.634
So that's what we're here
to talk about.

00:00:45.634 --> 00:00:48.501
We're gonna, first of all,
talk a little bit about

00:00:48.501 --> 00:00:50.968
some--
what users expect

00:00:50.968 --> 00:00:52.801
or are looking for
in accessible products.

00:00:52.801 --> 00:00:54.734
And I'll just make a point

00:00:54.734 --> 00:00:56.968
that we're gonna go into
some particular use cases

00:00:56.968 --> 00:00:59.601
but the range of accessibility
is wide.

00:00:59.601 --> 00:01:01.534
There are a lot of
different use cases,

00:01:01.534 --> 00:01:04.734
ways that we'd like to make
our applications accessible.

00:01:04.734 --> 00:01:07.934
What we're gonna talk about
forms a framework

00:01:07.934 --> 00:01:10.300
for many different modes
of accessibility, um,

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:13.367
that users can take advantage of
in your apps.

00:01:13.367 --> 00:01:15.834
We're gonna talk about
how you build accessibility

00:01:15.834 --> 00:01:19.634
specifically in our products
Chrome and Android.

00:01:19.634 --> 00:01:22.601
And then we're gonna show you
what tools we have

00:01:22.601 --> 00:01:25.901
to both build and test
these applications.

00:01:25.901 --> 00:01:28.033
We're gonna follow with
some cool demos.

00:01:28.033 --> 00:01:31.300
We're gonna show you what we
think are inspirational

00:01:31.300 --> 00:01:33.000
applications that show off

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:35.801
some of the best features
in accessibility.

00:01:35.801 --> 00:01:38.000
Rosenthal: So you're
probably asking yourself--

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:39.434
granted, most of you
seem to know

00:01:39.434 --> 00:01:40.901
a lot about accessibility
already--

00:01:40.901 --> 00:01:42.567
but a lot of people ask,
"Why should I care?

00:01:42.567 --> 00:01:44.868
Why should I make
my product accessible?"

00:01:44.868 --> 00:01:46.300
Well, there's a number
of reasons.

00:01:46.300 --> 00:01:48.467
Number one is actually
it makes financial sense

00:01:48.467 --> 00:01:49.868
for your company.

00:01:49.868 --> 00:01:52.701
The government and education
tend to have requirements

00:01:52.701 --> 00:01:55.601
for accessibility in the
products that they purchase,

00:01:55.601 --> 00:01:57.300
and they're very large
contracts,

00:01:57.300 --> 00:02:00.367
very large groups that you can
sell your products into.

00:02:00.367 --> 00:02:01.934
So it's really important
to make sure

00:02:01.934 --> 00:02:03.334
that your products
are accessible

00:02:03.334 --> 00:02:05.033
so that you can compete
in that marketplace

00:02:05.033 --> 00:02:08.300
and get them as large-paying
customers, right?

00:02:08.300 --> 00:02:11.033
The main reason
that government and education

00:02:11.033 --> 00:02:12.767
want products
to be accessible

00:02:12.767 --> 00:02:15.968
are so that students
can continue to learn

00:02:15.968 --> 00:02:18.167
and learn alongside
sighted students

00:02:18.167 --> 00:02:19.968
and hearing students
in school

00:02:19.968 --> 00:02:24.467
and so that as people grow
and move into the workplace

00:02:24.467 --> 00:02:26.534
that they can continue to work
alongside their peers

00:02:26.534 --> 00:02:28.667
in companies like ours,
right?

00:02:28.667 --> 00:02:31.534
Also, I know for me,

00:02:31.534 --> 00:02:33.767
it always helps me
when I work on something

00:02:33.767 --> 00:02:36.033
that enables people
to do something

00:02:36.033 --> 00:02:37.667
they weren't able
to do before.

00:02:37.667 --> 00:02:39.167
That feels great,

00:02:39.167 --> 00:02:41.434
and I like working on
accessibility because of that,

00:02:41.434 --> 00:02:43.701
that it's really--it's a good
feel-good thing, right?

00:02:43.701 --> 00:02:46.000
You know, so you can see that
people weren't able to do this,

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:47.033
and now they can.

00:02:47.033 --> 00:02:48.467
Wonderful.

00:02:48.467 --> 00:02:51.801
Also, there's a lot of
additional technology benefit

00:02:51.801 --> 00:02:53.267
to making your products
accessible.

00:02:53.267 --> 00:02:56.834
A lot of underlying technologies
that you put into your products

00:02:56.834 --> 00:02:58.968
will benefit you
in other ways.

00:02:58.968 --> 00:03:01.734
So for example,
with Android,

00:03:01.734 --> 00:03:03.701
when we were making it
accessible,

00:03:03.701 --> 00:03:05.901
we added a text to speech
engine.

00:03:05.901 --> 00:03:07.834
Well, later that came in handy

00:03:07.834 --> 00:03:09.534
as a way to do
driving directions

00:03:09.534 --> 00:03:11.033
in the maps application.

00:03:11.033 --> 00:03:12.501
We already had
the text engine there,

00:03:12.501 --> 00:03:13.801
so it could just
rely on it there.

00:03:13.801 --> 00:03:15.434
Green: That's right, Erin.
As a matter of fact,

00:03:15.434 --> 00:03:17.434
there's a lot of other places
where accessibility

00:03:17.434 --> 00:03:19.300
is kind of like a moon mission.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:21.534
The technologies we develop

00:03:21.534 --> 00:03:24.501
that are for helping people
access the platform

00:03:24.501 --> 00:03:26.167
are usable to everybody.

00:03:26.167 --> 00:03:28.234
Matter of fact,
they help all of your users.

00:03:28.234 --> 00:03:30.000
For example,
in keyboard access,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.601
we as developers, we rely
heavily on keyboard shortcuts.

00:03:33.601 --> 00:03:36.400
Adding keyboard access
to your applications

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:38.133
may be the number one thing
for web apps

00:03:38.133 --> 00:03:40.133
that you can do
to make it more accessible.

00:03:40.133 --> 00:03:43.167
Not just for folks who might
not be able to use a mouse,

00:03:43.167 --> 00:03:44.367
but for everybody.

00:03:44.367 --> 00:03:45.467
Like I want a hot key

00:03:45.467 --> 00:03:47.634
for almost every one
of the special--

00:03:47.634 --> 00:03:50.968
every one of the use cases
that I have in an application.

00:03:50.968 --> 00:03:54.234
There are some technologies
like text to speech

00:03:54.234 --> 00:03:56.634
and speech recognition
that were once thought of

00:03:56.634 --> 00:03:59.601
as exotic interface elements--

00:03:59.601 --> 00:04:00.868
are now becoming commonplace.

00:04:00.868 --> 00:04:02.400
You notice on Android

00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:07.300
I can add a speech
recognition element, um...

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:08.534
to take input.

00:04:08.534 --> 00:04:10.767
Also on many devices,

00:04:10.767 --> 00:04:13.100
we have the ability
to give vibrational feedback,

00:04:13.100 --> 00:04:14.334
what we call haptics.

00:04:14.334 --> 00:04:15.968
And video game developers
found out

00:04:15.968 --> 00:04:17.367
if they made
the controller vibrate

00:04:17.367 --> 00:04:19.667
when different events happen
in the UI,

00:04:19.667 --> 00:04:21.868
it becomes a much more
real experience.

00:04:21.868 --> 00:04:24.467
The same is true
for my applications

00:04:24.467 --> 00:04:28.367
when I can give some input
to the user that's not--

00:04:28.367 --> 00:04:30.100
doesn't need to be overt.

00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:31.834
I can make the device vibrate

00:04:31.834 --> 00:04:34.367
and make it seem like
a real part of my world.

00:04:34.367 --> 00:04:36.934
When I caption video streams,

00:04:36.934 --> 00:04:39.734
it not only opens up the video

00:04:39.734 --> 00:04:41.701
to folks who can't hear,

00:04:41.701 --> 00:04:43.868
it allows me to do
really interesting things--

00:04:43.868 --> 00:04:45.801
like you can run the captions

00:04:45.801 --> 00:04:47.767
through a service
like Google Translate,

00:04:47.767 --> 00:04:49.634
and all of a sudden,
all of the people

00:04:49.634 --> 00:04:51.400
who aren't native speakers

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:54.167
can now access
the video content.

00:04:54.167 --> 00:04:58.133
Customizable UIs,
as one example--

00:04:58.133 --> 00:05:00.434
in Gmail, I can set my theme

00:05:00.434 --> 00:05:03.901
and be able to set...

00:05:03.901 --> 00:05:07.267
theme elements, backgrounds,
contrast, colors

00:05:07.267 --> 00:05:10.067
might be kind of a nice thing,
personalization--

00:05:10.067 --> 00:05:12.033
adding bling
to my environment--

00:05:12.033 --> 00:05:15.734
might be actually
also required for some folks

00:05:15.734 --> 00:05:17.701
who need different contrast,
different colors,

00:05:17.701 --> 00:05:19.868
different magnification
in my application.

00:05:19.868 --> 00:05:22.601
Testability, finally.

00:05:22.601 --> 00:05:25.267
Turns out that if I'm building
an automated test,

00:05:25.267 --> 00:05:28.467
it has a lot of the same needs
that, say, a blind user needs.

00:05:28.467 --> 00:05:30.467
Like my automated test
can't use the mouse

00:05:30.467 --> 00:05:33.067
and usually
can't read the screen,

00:05:33.067 --> 00:05:36.067
and so these
accessibility features

00:05:36.067 --> 00:05:40.567
form a very stable API
for me to build

00:05:40.567 --> 00:05:42.434
automated tests against.

00:05:42.434 --> 00:05:43.834
Let's go next.

00:05:43.834 --> 00:05:46.133
Rosenthal: So let's talk
a little bit about the users,

00:05:46.133 --> 00:05:48.968
people who use
accessible technology.

00:05:48.968 --> 00:05:51.100
It's really important
for you to understand them

00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:54.000
and how they interact
with your products,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
just like all your other
users, right?

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:57.534
So the main thing
to keep in mind

00:05:57.534 --> 00:05:59.701
are the input and output
technologies that they use

00:05:59.701 --> 00:06:02.367
and making sure that you have
multiple redundant ways

00:06:02.367 --> 00:06:04.067
of interacting
with your applications--

00:06:04.067 --> 00:06:06.234
basically not relying
on a mouse,

00:06:06.234 --> 00:06:07.734
not relying on rollovers

00:06:07.734 --> 00:06:09.033
to be able to get
to your content.

00:06:09.033 --> 00:06:11.133
So main ones to keep in mind

00:06:11.133 --> 00:06:14.200
are for input using
keyboard and voice and touch,

00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:16.100
and then some special
purpose displays

00:06:16.100 --> 00:06:18.400
like this Braille display
that we have pictured here

00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:20.033
where you can do corded input.

00:06:20.033 --> 00:06:21.634
And then also for feedback--

00:06:21.634 --> 00:06:23.400
feedback's really vital
so that your user knows

00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:24.734
where they are on the screen

00:06:24.734 --> 00:06:26.000
and what
they're interacting with

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:27.868
at all points in time, right?

00:06:27.868 --> 00:06:29.467
So you should
make sure to have, again,

00:06:29.467 --> 00:06:30.868
redundant feedback as well.

00:06:30.868 --> 00:06:33.567
So not only have speech
but other audio cues

00:06:33.567 --> 00:06:38.100
for when tasks complete or other
notifications are happening,

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:39.767
and also vibration feedback,

00:06:39.767 --> 00:06:41.434
so that you get
that sense of reality

00:06:41.434 --> 00:06:43.000
when you're using the product.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:44.934
Plus, keep in mind other things
like the Braille display

00:06:44.934 --> 00:06:46.634
that we have here
as another input--

00:06:46.634 --> 00:06:50.267
or output device,
in this case.

00:06:50.267 --> 00:06:52.634
Green: Okay. So we've got
a list of a couple things,

00:06:52.634 --> 00:06:54.000
some sort of rules of thumb

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.334
for making accessible
applications...

00:06:56.334 --> 00:06:58.834
how to think about
what sort of features

00:06:58.834 --> 00:07:00.601
I need to pay attention to
as a developer.

00:07:00.601 --> 00:07:02.367
First of all,
I kind of mentioned this.

00:07:02.367 --> 00:07:04.067
Make sure
that all of my use cases

00:07:04.067 --> 00:07:07.367
can actually be completed
without using a pointing device.

00:07:07.367 --> 00:07:09.000
How do I do this?

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:10.901
Well, I unplug my mouse,

00:07:10.901 --> 00:07:12.467
and I try and use
the application.

00:07:12.467 --> 00:07:15.133
Usually, this means
that I'll have implemented

00:07:15.133 --> 00:07:17.434
keyboard shortcuts
that I make sure that the--

00:07:17.434 --> 00:07:19.968
if it's a web app,
that the tab order makes sense

00:07:19.968 --> 00:07:21.634
and that I can actually
focus on

00:07:21.634 --> 00:07:23.834
every element on the screen.

00:07:23.834 --> 00:07:27.901
I also want to make sure
that I am managing focus well

00:07:27.901 --> 00:07:29.234
inside my application.

00:07:29.234 --> 00:07:31.968
For example,
if I'm using HTML

00:07:31.968 --> 00:07:34.567
to simulate a modal dialog,

00:07:34.567 --> 00:07:37.033
I wanna make sure that
I'm actually trapping events

00:07:37.033 --> 00:07:39.567
so that if the user's trying
to tab through the elements

00:07:39.567 --> 00:07:42.634
that they can't actually
reach the elements

00:07:42.634 --> 00:07:47.133
that are behind my, uh,
my floating dialog box.

00:07:47.133 --> 00:07:49.167
If you want more information
on this,

00:07:49.167 --> 00:07:51.267
we've got a session tomorrow
which does a deep dive

00:07:51.267 --> 00:07:54.100
on building accessible
HTML applications.

00:07:54.100 --> 00:07:59.000
Depending on whether I'm on
Android or on the web,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.434
there are several
declarative ways

00:08:01.434 --> 00:08:03.834
that I can tell
assistive technologies

00:08:03.834 --> 00:08:05.868
how to interact
with my application--

00:08:05.868 --> 00:08:08.634
in the markup in the XML
for my Android application

00:08:08.634 --> 00:08:11.634
or in the HTML
for my web-based application.

00:08:11.634 --> 00:08:13.167
We'll go into a little bit
of this,

00:08:13.167 --> 00:08:16.467
uh, and we have talks here
at I/O that go

00:08:16.467 --> 00:08:19.367
much more into depth
on both of these.

00:08:19.367 --> 00:08:21.701
And then lastly,
for me as a developer,

00:08:21.701 --> 00:08:25.300
if I'm building
custom controls--

00:08:25.300 --> 00:08:27.968
things that aren't part
of the standard widget set--

00:08:27.968 --> 00:08:30.400
either on Android
or if I'm, you know,

00:08:30.400 --> 00:08:32.234
putting a bunch of DIVs together
to look like

00:08:32.234 --> 00:08:35.968
some kind of crazy new control
in HTML,

00:08:35.968 --> 00:08:38.200
I'm gonna have to do a little
bit of extra work

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:40.400
to add accessibility
support there.

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:43.634
And finally,
uh, I just need to test it.

00:08:43.634 --> 00:08:45.133
Um, it's--it's--

00:08:45.133 --> 00:08:47.868
Uh, it's certainly disappointing
if I make--

00:08:47.868 --> 00:08:49.534
put a lot of--
put some work into

00:08:49.534 --> 00:08:52.000
making my application
to be accessible

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.234
and then find out that
maybe my login screen

00:08:54.234 --> 00:08:55.334
is not accessible.

00:08:55.334 --> 00:08:56.567
So I want to make sure
that I test

00:08:56.567 --> 00:08:59.801
all the flows with the--
uh, assistive technologies

00:08:59.801 --> 00:09:03.133
that I'm targeting.

00:09:03.133 --> 00:09:04.868
Rosenthal: So what we're really
talking about here

00:09:04.868 --> 00:09:06.467
are creating these
empowering products

00:09:06.467 --> 00:09:07.868
that enable independence.

00:09:07.868 --> 00:09:10.100
These are products that work
out of the box,

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:12.400
are easy to use,
that someone can set up

00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:14.634
on their self--
by themselves,

00:09:14.634 --> 00:09:17.200
and that are really easy
to learn and, um,

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:18.868
provide that good feedback
so that they

00:09:18.868 --> 00:09:20.868
can get familiar
with the environment.

00:09:20.868 --> 00:09:22.934
Um, this is such
a liberating feeling,

00:09:22.934 --> 00:09:24.467
being able to do this
all on your own,

00:09:24.467 --> 00:09:26.000
and it's really the right
thing to do.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.200
Um, also, as Brad said,
keep in mind

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:30.701
to test your entire product
and not just think of,

00:09:30.701 --> 00:09:32.634
like, the main part
of your interface,

00:09:32.634 --> 00:09:34.834
but that from login
through documentation

00:09:34.834 --> 00:09:37.000
and even your help center,
that all of that

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:40.300
is also accessible.

00:09:40.300 --> 00:09:43.067
Green: Okay, I want to take
a little bit of a closer look

00:09:43.067 --> 00:09:47.334
at building web applications
and what makes those accessible.

00:09:47.334 --> 00:09:49.667
So if we get
in the way-back machine

00:09:49.667 --> 00:09:52.901
and think back to the '90s
when the web was simple,

00:09:52.901 --> 00:09:55.634
uh, how many of you
used Mosaic?

00:09:55.634 --> 00:09:57.434
Oh, a bunch of us are old.

00:09:57.434 --> 00:09:58.567
Okay, good.

00:09:58.567 --> 00:10:02.667
Um, accessibility
back then, uh,

00:10:02.667 --> 00:10:04.267
was a simple problem.

00:10:04.267 --> 00:10:05.868
Um, usually app--
uh, you know,

00:10:05.868 --> 00:10:07.067
web pages looked like this.

00:10:07.067 --> 00:10:08.434
It was a bunch of text
and links

00:10:08.434 --> 00:10:09.901
and maybe some images.

00:10:09.901 --> 00:10:13.801
And accessibility meant adding
alt tags to images.

00:10:13.801 --> 00:10:15.501
Matter of fact,
lot of us used alt tags

00:10:15.501 --> 00:10:17.367
when my modem was too slow.

00:10:17.367 --> 00:10:20.267
I'd turn images off and I'd just
read what the alt tags said.

00:10:20.267 --> 00:10:21.934
But the world has changed.

00:10:21.934 --> 00:10:24.133
Now even our most
simple applications

00:10:24.133 --> 00:10:26.801
like Google Search have become
very rich and interactive,

00:10:26.801 --> 00:10:29.567
so that as I'm typing,
Google Search updates

00:10:29.567 --> 00:10:31.667
my complete set
of search results.

00:10:31.667 --> 00:10:34.033
So we need to think differently
